@node "purpose" "What made for?"

   @{B}PURPOSE@{UB}

   Pix2Homepage just simplifies homepage creation for image gallerys.

   The  user  only  has  to  define the HTML sources including keywords,
which  were  replaced  by  thumbnail  lists,  the image(s), two browsing
elements  for  'next'  and  'previous'  and  a  comment  for each image.
Additionally  there  is space for a index file, a intro file (first page
shown, when using frames), list file and the image files.

   Pix2Homepage then generates the list, intro, index file and the image
files.   Each  image in the database get its image file, which source is
defined in the image page attribute.

   Additionally  you can store and load the contents of the database for
further  usage.   This  allowes  editing  different  image galleries.  A
special  feature is scaling the original image by a percental value when
displaying in the image pages.



@endnode



@node "templates" "HTML sources"

   @{B}TEMPLATES@{UB}

   Four  templates  are  used  by Pix2Homepage.  Its task is to hold the
source  and  keywords  for  HTML  file  creation.   The filenames of the
resulting files were discussed in the chapter @{"Resulting files" link "results"}.


· @{U}Template Index@{UU}:
   This file represents the first page of the gallery.  Usually the user
has  to define a frameset with two frames.  The first frame should point
to  the list page (generated by list template) and the second and bigger
one  to  the  intro page (generated by intro template).  The image pages
(generated by image template) are also shown in the bigger frame.

   For example:
@{B}
      <HTML>
         <HEAD>
            <TITLE>Image gallery</TITLE>
         </HEAD>
      
         <FRAMESET ROWS="100,*">
            <FRAME NAME="gallery_list"  SRC="gallery_list.html" >
            <FRAME NAME="gallery_image" SRC="gallery_intro.html">
         </FRAMESET>
      </HTML>
@{UB}
   This  generates  two frames: Upper frame is 100 pixels height holding
the  list  page,  the  lower  one fills the rest of space containing the
intro page (when called first).

   Normally this template does not have @{"keywords" link "keywords"}.


· @{U}Template Intro@{UU}:
   When using frames the resulting file of this template shows the start
page  in  the  image  frame.  The  text may contain some notes about the
images or some something else.

   For example:
@{B}
      <HTML>
         <HEAD>
            <TITLE>Image gallery</TITLE>
         </HEAD>
      
         <BODY>
            This is a image gallery of my last holiday on Antigua.<BR>
            <BR>
            Select the thumbnails above &amp; have fun!
         </BODY>
      </HTML>
@{UB}
   This shows a short message about the last vacation.

   Normally this template does not have @{"keywords" link "keywords"}.


· @{U}Template List@{UU}:

   This  template is used to generate thumbnail lists. Each image stored
in database will get a according miniature in the list. @{B}As this database
is very simple, there have to be real thumbnail image files. These files
have  the  same  filename  like the images, but with prefix 's'. A image
called  "MonaLisa.jpg"  must  have its thumbnail file "sMonaLisa.jpg" in
the same directory!@{UB}  I prefer thumbnail files with a image size of about
80x80 pixels considering the image aspect.

   For example:
@{B}
      <HTML>
         <HEAD>
            <TITLE>Image gallery</TITLE>
            <BASE TARGET="gallery_image">
         </HEAD>
      
         <BODY>
         <!-- THUMBNAILS_HORIZONTAL -->
         </BODY>
      
      </HTML>
@{UB}
   As  you  can  see  the  "<!-- THUMBNAILS_HORIZONTAL -->" is a keyword
which  will  be  replaced by the list of thumbnails.  The "<BASE>" entry
avoids  jumping into other frames.  If you change the frame name for the
image  pages  in  the index template you also have to alter the "<BASE>"
value.

   Allowed @{"keywords" link "keywords"} are:
   - "<!-- THUMBNAILS_HORIZONTAL -->"
   - "<!-- THUMBNAILS_VERTICAL -->"


· @{U}Template Image@{UU}:
   The main template is the template for each image.

   For example:
@{B}
      <HTML>
         <HEAD>
            <TITLE>Image gallery</TITLE>
            <BASE TARGET="gallery_image">
         </HEAD>
      
         <BODY>
            <CENTER>
            <!-- IMAGE -->
            <TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5>
               <TR>
                  <TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="1%">
                     <!-- PREVIOUS_IMAGE -->
                  </TD>
                  <TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH="98%">
                     <!-- COMMENT -->
                  </TD>
                  <TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH="1%">
                     <!-- NEXT_IMAGE -->
                  </TD>
               </TR>
            </TABLE>
            </CENTER>
         </BODY>
      </HTML>
@{UB}
   This  is  a  bit  complicated, but it isn't.  Hidden in this template
there  are  four  keywords:   "<!-- IMAGE -->"  for  the  inline  image,
"<!-- PREVIOUS_IMAGE -->"  for  a  link  to  the previous image in list,
"<!-- NEXT_IMAGE -->"  for  a  link  to  the  next  image  in  list  and
"<!-- COMMENT -->"  for  the  comment  to/about  the image.  The example
generates  a  table  containing  the link back, the comment and the link
forward (left to right).  Above the table the image is placed centered.

   Allowed @{"keywords" link "keywords"} are:
   - "<!-- THUMBNAILS_HORIZONTAL -->"
   - "<!-- THUMBNAILS_VERTICAL -->"
   - "<!-- IMAGE -->"
   - "<!-- PREVIOUS_IMAGE -->"
   - "<!-- NEXT_IMAGE -->"
   - "<!-- COMMENT -->"


@endnode



@node keywords "For use in templates"

   @{B}KEYWORDS@{UB}

   Keywords are used to be replaced by HTML sequences generated from the
records in the image table.  They were placed in the four templates.


   Known keywords:

· @{B}<!-- THUMBNAILS_HORIZONTAL -->@{UB}:
   This generates a row of thumbnail images.  The images are embedded in
a horizontal table like following:
@{B}
      <TABLE>
         <TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>
            <TD><A HREF="image001.html"><IMG SRC="../pix/simage001.jpg" WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=56 ALT="image001.jpg" BORDER=0></A></TD>
            <TD><A HREF="image002.html"><IMG SRC="../pix/simage002.jpg" WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=56 ALT="image002.jpg" BORDER=0></A></TD>
            <TD><A HREF="image003.html"><IMG SRC="../pix/simage003.jpg" WIDTH=56 HEIGHT=80 ALT="image003.jpg" BORDER=0></A></TD>
            <!-- ... -->
         </TR>
      </TABLE>
@{UB}
   Every link filename and thumbnail name depends on the filename of the
original   image.    In  the  example  the  first  image  has  the  name
"image001.jpg".    Pix2Homepages  now  generates  a  image  file  called
"image001.html",  where  "<A>" points to, and the thumbnail filename got
its  prefix  "s", so that the miniature image is called "simage001.jpg".
The  user  itself must generate that thumbnail and store it with exactly
this name.


· @{B}<!-- THUMBNAILS_VERTICAL -->@{UB}:
   This  generates  a  column  of  thumbnail  images.   Analogue  to the
horizontal version the miniatures were embedded in a vertical table:
@{B}
      <TABLE>
         <TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>
            <TD><A HREF="image001.html"><IMG SRC="../pix/simage001.jpg" WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=56 ALT="image001.jpg" BORDER=0></A></TD>
         </TR>
         <TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>
            <TD><A HREF="image002.html"><IMG SRC="../pix/simage002.jpg" WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=56 ALT="image002.jpg" BORDER=0></A></TD>
         </TR>
         <TR ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE>
            <TD><A HREF="image003.html"><IMG SRC="../pix/simage003.jpg" WIDTH=56 HEIGHT=80 ALT="image003.jpg" BORDER=0></A></TD>
         </TR>
         <!-- ... -->
      </TABLE>
@{UB}
   For a short description see "<!-- THUMBNAILS_HORIZONTAL -->".


· @{B}<!-- IMAGE -->@{UB}:
   This keyword inserts a embedded image, which shows the original image
in  its  origin size.  Additionally, the user can change the size of the
original  image  by  changing the value @{I}Image scale @{UI}in the database.  It
defaults  to  100%.   If  the  value  isn't  100,  so  the database also
generates a link to the original image itself and a short note.  Look at
a generated example:
@{B}
      <A HREF="../pix/image002.jpg">
         <IMG SRC="../pix/image002.jpg" WIDTH=337 HEIGHT=235 ALT="image002.jpg" BORDER=0>
      </A><BR>
      <FONT SIZE=1>Click on image to see original size (now 50%)</FONT>
@{UB}
   The  database generates only one line, but for the example I splitted
the  line  into  several  lines.   The example shows a replacement for a
image  which  is  scaled  down  to 50%.  The little note below the image
informs  the user about that fact.  If the internet surfer clicks on the
image,  he  gets  the  pure  image, but no new HTML file with a embedded
image.   As  you  might have detected, the scaled image and the link are
using  the  same  image  file.  This leads to a fast link from scaled to
original image and vice versa, when the browser's cache is turned on.

   If the user doesn't change the @{I}Image scale @{UI}value of 100, the database
only replaces the keyword to:
@{B}
      <IMG SRC="../pix/image002.jpg" WIDTH=674 HEIGHT=471 ALT="image002.jpg" BORDER=0>
@{UB}


· @{B}<!-- COMMENT -->@{UB}:
   The  comment  attribute  of  the  image  table  will be used for this
replacement.   Everything  in  this attribute will simply be embedded in
the  according template.  Therefore you should pay attention for special
characters  like '>', '<', '&', german umlauts, french acutes and so on.
If  used,  they  better  should  be replaced by their entities like e.g.
'&gt;', '&lt;', '&amp;', '&auml;', '&szlig;', '&aacute;'.


· @{B}<!-- PREVIOUS_IMAGE -->@{UB}:
   This  generates a link to the previous image in list.  If there is no
previous  image  (current  image  is  first one in list), simply 'Start'
without  a  link  is  shown.   Otherwise  a blue box containing a linked
'Previous' appears.


· @{B}<!-- NEXT_IMAGE -->@{UB}:
   Analogue to "<!-- PREVIOUS_IMAGE -->" a linked 'Next' with a blue box
around is shown, otherwise the text 'End'.



@endnode



@node results "Files after building gallery"

   @{B}RESULTS@{UB}

   The Pix2Homepage file generator builds at least three files:

· Index file (Name build with @{B}Prefix@{UB} attribute and "_index.html")
· Intro file (Name build with @{B}Prefix@{UB} attribute and "_intro.html")
· List file (Name build with @{B}Prefix@{UB} attribute and "_list.html")

   In  addition, as much images as entries in the database, MUIbase will
generate  image files.  The names were build using the @{B}Prefix@{UB} attribute,
the image name (basename without file extension) and ".html".

   All  files  were  stored  in the directory specified by the attribute
@{B}Local Path@{UB}.   Then  you can put these files onto a server or test it out
using the local entries as described in the @{"attributes" link "attributes"} section.



@endnode



@node attributes "The attributes in the database"

   @{B}ATTRIBUTES@{UB}

   For  better  understanding  of  the first five attributes, you should
imagine  following  file  structure  of  your  destination  server @{I}after @{UI}
generation of all files:
@{B}
      .
      +- pix
      |  +- image001.jpg
      |  +- image002.jpg
      |  +- image003.jpg
      |  +- simage001.jpg
      |  +- simage002.jpg
      |  \\- simage003.jpg
      |
      +- gallery_image001.html
      +- gallery_image002.html
      +- gallery_image003.html
      +- gallery_index.html
      +- gallery_intro.html
      +- gallery_list.html
@{UB}

· @{U}Image path@{UU}
   This  path  is  used  for the links to the images.  I recommend using
relative  path names.  In our above example, you have to enter
      @{B}pix/@{UB}
You  also  can  generate  such  gallerys  for local usage using the same
entry,  but if you intend to print the generated files in @{B}T:@{UB}, though the
images e.g.  are in the directory @{B}PICS:gallery@{UB}, you have to enter a full
URI like
      @{B}file:///PICS:gallery/@{UB}
(when using Voyager) or
      @{B}file://localhost/PICS:gallery/@{UB}
You cannot simply enter the path @{B}PICS:gallery@{UB}, because a hyperlink
      @{B}PICS:gallery/image002.jpg@{UB}
doesn't work (Voyager states, that PICS is no valid transfer protocol).

   Also keep in mind:
   @{B}Do not forget@{UB} a trailing slash '/', if neccessary !!!


· @{U}Prefix@{UU}
   The Prefix is used to generate the filenames. Each generated file
gets this prefix including a '_' (see example above). According to the
example, you have to enter
      @{B}gallery@{UB}

   You also can write complete paths, but keep the structure of your web
server  in  mind.   When you nest into directories, you have to nest out
the picture links.

   Example:
      @{B}gallery/pix@{UB}
A according file could then be
      @{B}gallery/pix_image003.html@{UB}
When you now insert a link to a picture in that HTML file, you must nest
out one directory by entering
      @{B}../pix/@{UB}
in  the  @{B}Image Path@{UB} attribute, otherwise the browser looks for the image
in the @{B}gallery/pix@{UB}, not in the @{B}pix@{UB} directory!


· @{U}File path@{UU}
   This file path is only needed when using a gallery on local machines.
For server files, the attribute is empty.  The file path is only used in
hyperlinks  ("<A>").   Currently  it  isn't possible to split the index,
intro  and list files from the image files.  All generated files resides
in one directory.

   For  example, if the images are in the directory @{B}PICS:gallery@{UB} and you
want to generate the files to @{B}T:@{UB}, you have to enter
      @{B}file:///T:@{UB}
(when using Voyager) or
      @{B}file://localhost/T:@{UB}

   Also keep in mind:
   @{B}Do not forget@{UB} a trailing slash '/', if neccessary !!!


· @{U}Image scale@{UU}
   This  is a nice feature of this database.  Usually the original image
will  be  shown when you click on the thumbnail image.  Sometimes nearly
all  images  of  a  image  collection  are bigger than frame size or the
images  are  too small, so you can set a scaling value in percent.  This
scales the size of the original image and creates a embedded image using
the  new  dimension.   A value of 100 means original size.  If the value
isn't  100,  the  database additionally generates a link to the original
image  itself  and a short note containing the message @{B}Click on image to
see  original  size  (now  x%)@{UB}, where x is the percentage.  At a scaling
factor  of  100, no link will be created, because you are still watching
the original.


· @{U}Local path@{UU}
   This path is used for MUIbase, where it should write the generated
files to. This entry is independent from the file generation.


· @{U}Help file for Pix2Homepage@{UU}
   The  guide  file  you  are currently reading can be directly accessed
over  this  attribute.   Right of the file requester button right of the
string  field,  you  might  detect a 'V' (or in the german version 'A').
When  you  press  this button, MUIbase launches MultiView for displaying
the guide (supposing you have defined MultiView in the preferences).

   The  entry in this attribute will always be stored and never deleted,
so  choose  the @{B}Pix2Homepage.guide@{UB} and save the project.  Now you always
can access to the information you need.



The next four attributes are used for each image in the database.

· @{U}Image@{UU}
   Filename  of  the  image.  To view the image press the 'V' (or 'A' at
german  catalog)  right  of the string field.  This filename is the base
for  the  generated  image  files.   MUIbase  truncates  the name to the
basename without extension and works with it.


· @{U}Size@{UU}
   The two attributes hold the width and height of the image in pixels.
Currently you have to fill out the fields manually.

   @{B}NEVER@{UB}  leave  these  fields  empty,  because it surely leads to empty
image files!


· @{U}Thumbnail@{UU}
   The  two  attributes hold the width and height of the thumbnail image
in pixels.  Currently you have to fill out the fields manually.

   @{B}NEVER@{UB}  leave  these  fields  empty,  because it surely leads to empty
image files!


· @{U}Comment@{UU}
   This  is  simply  the  text  which will be displayed below the image.
Everything in this attribute will simply be embedded in the image files.
Therefore you should pay attention for special characters like '>', '<',
'&', german umlauts, french acutes and so on, who could collide with the
HTML charset.  If used, they better should be replaced by their entities
like e.g.  '&gt;', '&lt;', '&amp;', '&auml;', '&szlig;', '&aacute;'.



@endnode



